of your emergency?

18
00:03:07,929 --> 00:03:09,863
Help!

19
00:03:10,932 --> 00:03:12,365
Help him!

20
00:03:13,701 --> 00:03:16,033
- Let's get a cold package, stat!
- Let me have the boy!

21
00:03:17,271 --> 00:03:21,264
To the burn unit!
It's okay now, sir.

22
00:03:21,342 --> 00:03:24,778
Put him in ER 8.
Sir, you have to stay with me now.

23
00:03:25,880 --> 00:03:28,872
- Are you the boy's father?
- No.

24
00:03:30,618 --> 00:03:32,313
He was just--

25
00:03:32,386 --> 00:03:35,685
He was walking down
the middle of the road.

26
00:03:35,757 --> 00:03:38,021
Have you seen him before?
What's his name?

27
00:03:39,694 --> 00:03:43,061
- Sir, please. It's important.
- What? What?

28
00:03:43,131 --> 00:03:47,295
- The boy's name!
- I don't know his name!

29
00:06:02,536 --> 00:06:05,528
Excuse me, Mr. Faraday?

30
00:06:05,606 --> 00:06:06,937
Yeah?

31
00:06:07,008 --> 00:06:08,942
We're Brady's parents.

32
00:06:11,746 --> 00:06:14,806
You feel like they're old enough.

33
00:06:14,882 --> 00:06:17,646
- They should be able to--
- Can't let them out of your sight.

34
00:06:17,718 --> 00:06:20,448
I mean, he said he was going
to the park to play.

35
00:06:20,521 --> 00:06:23,285
He didn't want us to know
what he was doing.

36
00:06:25,860 --> 00:06:28,761
Michael, we can't thank you enough.
It you hadn't come along when you did--

37
00:06:28,829 --> 00:06:31,127
No, I'm just glad we made it.

38
00:06:34,602 --> 00:06:36,900
So, uh...

39
00:06:36,971 --> 00:06:38,438
what, uh--

40
00:06:38,506 --> 00:06:41,942
He and his friends got together
all their fireworks--

41
00:06:42,009 --> 00:06:46,105
their cones and their candles--
and they tied them up together.

42
00:06:46,180 --> 00:06:49,308
They were trying to blast
some kind of super rocket in the park.

43
00:06:49,383 --> 00:06:51,510
And Brady's the one who--

44
00:06:51,585 --> 00:06:54,247
He must've been the one
that set it oft.

45
00:06:54,322 --> 00:06:56,916
The other kids must've
put him up to it.

46
00:07:00,895 --> 00:07:03,659
And it was just starting
to feel like home too.

47
00:07:03,731 --> 00:07:06,199
I thought that to myself today.

48
00:07:06,267 --> 00:07:09,634
Just thought it's starting
to feel like home.

49
00:07:14,008 --> 00:07:16,340
He's gonna be okay.

50
00:07:18,212 --> 00:07:20,407
He's gonna be all right.

51
00:07:22,950 --> 00:07:24,508
Thank you, Michael.

52
00:07:26,687 --> 00:07:28,621
Unit 14, clear.

53
00:07:30,091 --> 00:07:31,615
Oh, God.

54
00:07:31,692 --> 00:07:35,389
It's gotta be hell
they're going through.

55
00:07:35,463 --> 00:07:39,991
Two months they've lived there.
I haven't said one word to 'em.

56
00:07:41,635 --> 00:07:44,365
Well, you can't be
best friends with everybody.

57
00:07:44,438 --> 00:07:48,602
I watch them fixin' up their house,
their kids playin' in their yard.

58
00:07:48,676 --> 00:07:52,772
I held their son in my arms
hangin' on for his life tonight.

59
00:07:52,847 --> 00:07:55,338
Kid lives right across the street.

60
00:07:55,416 --> 00:07:57,543
I didn't even know his name.

61
00:08:18,372 --> 00:08:20,033
Did he die?

62
00:08:22,109 --> 00:08:26,205
No, he's gonna be in the hospital
for a while, but he'll be tine.

63
00:08:27,214 --> 00:08:30,547
I saw the blood in the street.

64
00:08:32,887 --> 00:08:34,821
He's gonna be okay, Grant.

65
00:08:37,892 --> 00:08:41,225
Brooke said that she made you
some dinner. You're not hungry?

66
00:08:47,601 --> 00:08:49,865
Want me to fix you something?

67
00:08:53,274 --> 00:08:54,707
Grant?

68
00:08:57,344 --> 00:09:02,213
- She gonna stay here every night?
- No, not every night.

69
00:09:04,852 --> 00:09:07,412
She stayed last night
because I asked her.

70
00:09:07,488 --> 00:09:10,548
We talked about Brooke.
You said you liked her.

71
00:09:10,624 --> 00:09:13,252
I liked her better before.

72
00:09:15,162 --> 00:09:16,595
Yeah, well...

73
00:09:20,134 --> 00:09:22,193
try to get some sleep, okay?

74
00:09:31,879 --> 00:09:33,039
Love you.

75
00:09:51,932 --> 00:09:54,594
The name of this course
is American Terrorism.

76
00:09:55,503 --> 00:09:58,904
Two hundred years ago, we fought
a revolution over certain beliefs--

77
00:09:58,973 --> 00:10:04,275
Liberty, justice for all,
self-rule and self- reliance.

78
00:10:04,345 --> 00:10:08,076
There are many in this country
who feel we have not yet won that war.

79
00:10:09,049 --> 00:10:11,847
Terrorist acts,
violent political theater--

80
00:10:11,919 --> 00:10:15,184
These have been a part of social dissent
in this country since its inception.

81
00:10:15,256 --> 00:10:19,090
But why?
Why here in this land of freedom?

82
00:10:19,160 --> 00:10:22,186
What's led men to such bloodshed...

83
00:10:22,263 --> 00:10:24,424
in the name of their beliefs?

84
00:10:24,498 --> 00:10:27,023
Why in this era
of national prosperity...

85
00:10:27,101 --> 00:10:30,502
has the antigovernment movement
been at its peak?

86
00:10:30,571 --> 00:10:34,507
And what's that gonna mean
when the prosperity fades?

87
00:10:34,575 --> 00:10:37,203
Fewer and fewer of us are voting.

88
00:10:37,278 --> 00:10:39,269
More and more of us are joining
the ranks of a resistance.

89
00:10:39,346 --> 00:10:43,146
How long are we gonna call
these numbers insignificant?

90
00:10:44,718 --> 00:10:47,949
What do they have to teach us?

91
00:11:06,774 --> 00:11:09,675
- I'm going to go explore.
- Okay.

92
00:11:21,088 --> 00:11:24,182
The only woman I ever liked havin'
around that was smarter than me.

93
00:11:24,258 --> 00:11:26,590
Whit Carver, generous to a fault.

94
00:11:32,333 --> 00:11:35,029
Good day, Mr. Faraday.

95
00:11:35,102 --> 00:11:37,730
- How's he doin'?
- He's all right.

96
00:11:37,805 --> 00:11:40,433
We're still seeing his counselor.

97
00:11:40,507 --> 00:11:43,101
She says he's improving,
but he still keeps to himself a lot.

98
00:11:44,945 --> 00:11:46,879
How's his dad doin'?

99
00:11:48,282 --> 00:11:50,182
He's all right.

100
00:11:50,251 --> 00:11:52,617
Still seeing his graduate student?

101
00:11:54,555 --> 00:11:56,921
Yeah. She says
he's improving, but--

102
00:11:56,991 --> 00:11:59,960
He still keeps to himself
a lot, huh?

103
00:12:02,463 --> 00:12:04,693
This kid they got me
partnered with...

104
00:12:04,765 --> 00:12:09,725
is a walking, laptop computer,
cyberspace geek.

105
00:12:09,803 --> 00:12:13,068
Put him across from some real bad guys,
it's like he's surprised to see 'em.

106
00:12:13,140 --> 00:12:16,541
- I ought to make him take your course.
- Really?

107
00:12:16,610 --> 00:12:18,840
- Teachin' it again?
- Oh, yeah.

108
00:12:20,547 --> 00:12:23,141
She'd like that.
I know what that would mean to her.

109
00:12:23,217 --> 00:12:27,153
The invitation's still good
for you to come by as a guest.

110
00:12:30,391 --> 00:12:32,882
I'd rather not stand trial
in front of you.

111
00:12:32,960 --> 00:12:37,795
- That's not what it would be.
- Yeah, right. I know what it would be.

112
00:12:41,702 --> 00:12:43,067
How's work?

113
00:12:44,204 --> 00:12:45,933
You know, we're a team.

114
00:12:49,209 --> 00:12:52,303
That's what I miss, you know?

115
00:12:52,379 --> 00:12:55,507
Conversations about work.
I'd tell her all about my day.

116
00:12:55,582 --> 00:12:58,016
She couldn't tell me
a goddamn thing.

117
00:12:59,853 --> 00:13:02,287
You wouldn't think I'd miss that,
but I do.

118
00:13:02,356 --> 00:13:05,792
Have me over to dinner sometime.
I'll keep some state secrets from you.

119
00:13:05,859 --> 00:13:08,987
- It'll be like she never left.
- People remember her, Whit?

120
00:13:11,031 --> 00:13:13,261
- What do you mean?
- At the Bureau.

121
00:13:13,334 --> 00:13:16,667
Do they remember,
or do people forget?

122
00:13:21,675 --> 00:13:24,007
They remember her, Michael.
They do.

123
00:13:28,482 --> 00:13:30,950
Leah died for her country.

124
00:13:32,953 --> 00:13:35,387
She shouldn't have.

125
00:13:43,897 --> 00:13:47,628
Michael, hello! How are you doing?
Our other guest of honor. Come in.

126
00:13:47,701 --> 00:13:50,261
- Hope we're not late.
- No. Oliver, Michael's here.

127
00:13:50,337 --> 00:13:52,498
- Cheryl, this is Brooke.
- Hi, it's nice to meet you.

128
00:13:52,573 --> 00:13:54,939
It's really nice to meet you too.

129
00:13:55,008 --> 00:13:58,671
And this must be Grant.
How are you doing?

130
00:13:58,746 --> 00:14:03,206
There's junk food in the kitchen that's
just for kids and not for grownups.

131
00:14:03,283 --> 00:14:07,151
- Come on in.
- Let me introduce you to some friends.

132
00:14:09,022 --> 00:14:11,957
- Hot dog, please.
- Brady's looking great.

133
00:14:12,025 --> 00:14:15,392
Yeah, so would you it you found a way
to get out of school for a while.

134
00:14:15,462 --> 00:14:20,058
You're right, I would.
I teach at G.W.-- American history.

135
00:14:21,468 --> 00:14:23,993
I was always bad in history.

136
00:14:24,071 --> 00:14:27,438
- Condemned to repeat it?
- Yeah, several times.

137
00:14:28,942 --> 00:14:31,934
So, what kind of work do you do?

138
00:14:32,012 --> 00:14:36,210
I'm a structural engineer.
You know the Reston Mall?

139
00:14:36,283 --> 00:14:39,980
- Oh, yeah.
- We're redesigning the addition.

140
00:14:40,053 --> 00:14:43,853
You want bigger storage, more parking?
I'm the guy to ask.

141
00:14:43,924 --> 00:14:47,121
He knows. I'm not sure he totally
understands what happened.

142
00:14:47,194 --> 00:14:49,594
You know Michael from--

143
00:14:49,663 --> 00:14:53,690
I was Michael's teaching assistant
in my first year of grad school.

144
00:14:53,767 --> 00:14:56,099
There was nothing between us.

145
00:14:56,170 --> 00:14:59,435
I knew his family.
I knew Leah.

146
00:15:00,207 --> 00:15:02,641
I mean, this thing,
this is kind of--

147
00:15:04,678 --> 00:15:06,737
kind of new between us.

148
00:15:06,814 --> 00:15:07,872
Wow.

149
00:15:09,683 --> 00:15:13,084
You're so sweet together.

150
00:15:13,153 --> 00:15:15,519
Of course,
I think the world of him.

151
00:15:15,589 --> 00:15:19,389
He's such a good man.

152
00:15:19,460 --> 00:15:21,394
Such a good father.

153
00:15:30,938 --> 00:15:33,133
The job was just
too appealing to pass up.

154
00:15:33,207 --> 00:15:35,801
Contracts were down
all over St. Louis.

155
00:15:35,876 --> 00:15:39,869
- How long were you in St. Louis?
- Four years, thereabouts.

156
00:15:39,947 --> 00:15:43,474
I grew up on a farm
in a place called Carson, Kansas.

157
00:15:44,551 --> 00:15:46,985
Never lived East before.

158
00:15:47,054 --> 00:15:49,215
Kids'll get to see
their first ocean.

159
00:15:49,289 --> 00:15:52,053
Yeah, I'm afraid
downtown's falling apart.

160
00:15:52,125 --> 00:15:56,425
That's what I hear. I guess we're
not in Kansas anymore, eh, Toto?

161
00:15:56,497 --> 00:15:57,589
Hannah.

162
00:15:58,665 --> 00:16:00,098
Bedtime.

163
00:16:02,336 --> 00:16:04,964
- Be careful of his hand!
- I haven't even got two hands!

164
00:16:10,844 --> 00:16:13,745
It's been a long time since
I've seen him just bein' a kid.

165
00:16:13,814 --> 00:16:15,611
Sometimes he's--

166
00:16:15,682 --> 00:16:18,116
You know, since his mother--

167
00:16:20,020 --> 00:16:23,387
He has a tough time
making friends sometimes.

168
00:16:25,859 --> 00:16:27,918
Well...

169
00:16:27,995 --> 00:16:30,691
Lucky we all need friends.

170
00:16:30,764 --> 00:16:33,062
Life just isn't the same
without 'em.

171
00:16:46,213 --> 00:16:48,773
Let me take this in. Dad?

172
00:16:48,849 --> 00:16:52,546
- Yeah?
- How do you spell "restricted"?

173
00:16:53,921 --> 00:16:56,822
Restricted. R-E-S-T-R-l--

174
00:16:57,624 --> 00:17:01,219
You know how to use the dictionary.
What are you guys doin' in there?

175
00:17:01,295 --> 00:17:03,320
Building a compound.

176
00:17:03,397 --> 00:17:05,957
- Compound?
- Soldiers' compound.

177
00:17:08,302 --> 00:17:09,667
Stop, Dad.

178
00:17:09,736 --> 00:17:12,330
You have to know
the secret handshake.

179
00:17:12,406 --> 00:17:14,340
Should we tell him?

180
00:17:17,010 --> 00:17:18,978
All right. Well...

181
00:17:19,046 --> 00:17:23,210
just so I know you're not gonna
use any fireworks in there, Brady.

182
00:17:23,283 --> 00:17:25,217
General Brady, Dad.

183
00:17:25,285 --> 00:17:28,721
Yeah?
No fireworks, General Brady.

184
00:17:28,789 --> 00:17:32,748
That's classified information.
You don't know the secret handshake.

185
00:17:32,826 --> 00:17:35,886
- I'm serious, Brady.
- Come on, Grant.

186
00:17:37,497 --> 00:17:40,091
Get washed up, guys.
We're gonna get dinner on.

187
00:17:56,149 --> 00:17:59,312
- Come on in.
- Got something for you in my mailbox.

188
00:17:59,386 --> 00:18:00,819
What's that?

189
00:18:01,822 --> 00:18:04,052
"University of Pennsylvania"?

190
00:18:04,124 --> 00:18:06,684
-I thought you hadn't lived East before.
-I haven't.

191
00:18:06,760 --> 00:18:10,719
I went to Kansas State, class of '78.
Must have me mixed up with someone else.

192
00:18:10,797 --> 00:18:14,665
- Same class, huh?
- Yeah, but at K State.

193
00:18:14,735 --> 00:18:17,033
It's a reunion.

194
00:18:17,104 --> 00:18:19,971
Must've lost track of some guy,
sent it to me instead.

195
00:18:20,040 --> 00:18:23,168
Sorry about the mess. Cheryl and the
girls are at a church group tonight.

196
00:18:23,243 --> 00:18:25,268
I'm trying to catch up
on a little work.

197
00:18:25,345 --> 00:18:27,404
- How are ya?
- Good.

198
00:18:27,481 --> 00:18:29,574
- How's Grant?
- He's doin' great.

199
00:18:31,318 --> 00:18:33,081
Excuse me a minute. Hello?

200
00:18:39,226 --> 00:18:41,626
Why don't I call you back?

201
00:18:43,397 --> 00:18:45,331
What do you mean?

202
00:18:46,466 --> 00:18:47,899
Okay.

203
00:18:50,303 --> 00:18:53,363
Well, we should really talk
in person about this.

204
00:18:53,440 --> 00:18:54,873
Yeah.

205
00:18:57,978 --> 00:19:00,003
I could work on this tonight.

206
00:19:00,080 --> 00:19:01,911
Okay. All right.

207
00:19:01,982 --> 00:19:03,950
Listen, hold on a second.

208
00:19:05,018 --> 00:19:08,044
This project is taking forever.
Client can't seem to make up his mind.

209
00:19:08,121 --> 00:19:11,215
- This the Reston Mall?
- Yeah. We're getting it on track.

210
00:19:11,291 --> 00:19:13,384
I'm sorry, I have to--

211
00:19:13,460 --> 00:19:16,293
- We'll see each other this weekend.
- Yes, the Junior Ds.

212
00:19:16,363 --> 00:19:20,094
- Brady keeps talking about it.
- Yeah, he's gonna love it.

213
00:19:20,167 --> 00:19:22,567
He's gonna make more friends
than he'll know what to do with.

214
00:19:22,636 --> 00:19:25,400
They do camp outs, trips.

215
00:19:25,472 --> 00:19:28,635
Give you the house to yourself...

216
00:19:28,709 --> 00:19:30,643
every now and then.

217
00:19:30,711 --> 00:19:32,804
You and Brooke, I mean.

218
00:19:33,980 --> 00:19:36,175
- I thank you, neighbor.
- For what?

219
00:19:36,249 --> 00:19:38,342
For having
a ten-year-old next door.

220
00:19:44,658 --> 00:19:47,821
- What do you know about shopping malls?
- Huh?

221
00:19:47,894 --> 00:19:52,456
Shopping malls. I was over at
the Langs', talking with Oliver.

222
00:19:52,532 --> 00:19:57,469
He had this blueprint on his counter.
He said it was the Reston Mall.

223
00:19:57,537 --> 00:20:00,233
- That's what he's workin' on.
- Yeah, but it wasn't.

224
00:20:01,308 --> 00:20:03,435
- What do you mean?
- I looked.

225
00:20:03,510 --> 00:20:07,344
It was a building.
It wasn't a mall.

226
00:20:07,414 --> 00:20:10,178
- Right, it's an addition.
- No.

227
00:20:11,251 --> 00:20:13,685
It was an office building.
It wasn't stores at all.

228
00:20:13,754 --> 00:20:17,281
oh, so, it's some other project
that he's working on.

229
00:20:21,795 --> 00:20:24,457
Why would he tell me
it was a mall if it wasn't?

230
00:20:24,531 --> 00:20:26,465
Why would he lie?

231
00:20:28,235 --> 00:20:31,762
When you took engineering in college,
what kind of grades did you get?

232
00:20:31,838 --> 00:20:33,772
I didn't take engineering.

233
00:20:40,580 --> 00:20:43,811
What I saw was an office building.

234
00:20:49,422 --> 00:20:50,616
Fourteen moths ago
on a Monday in January...

235
00:20:52,192 --> 00:20:55,252
over 60 federal employees
went to work like they always did...

236
00:20:55,328 --> 00:20:58,456
at the Roosevelt Federal Building
in downtown St. Louis.

237
00:21:00,200 --> 00:21:03,260
Except on that Monday
they didn't come home.

238
00:21:03,336 --> 00:21:05,827
In a truck parked in front...

239
00:21:05,906 --> 00:21:10,639
was hidden 50 pounds
of C-4 plastic explosive.

240
00:21:10,710 --> 00:21:14,510
When it was detonated, it disintegrated
the street side of the building...

241
00:21:14,581 --> 00:21:18,176
obliterating dozens
of government offices...

242
00:21:18,251 --> 00:21:20,776
the building's day care center...

243
00:21:21,688 --> 00:21:24,953
and the St. Louis branch
of the Internal Revenue Service...

