00:21:25,025 --> 00:21:28,426
which was ultimately determined
to be the target of the attack.

245
00:21:28,495 --> 00:21:33,194
The truck was leased by
this 33-year-old electrician...

246
00:21:34,634 --> 00:21:36,124
Dean Scobee.

247
00:21:36,903 --> 00:21:40,964
Scobee had served some prison time
for tax evasion...

248
00:21:41,041 --> 00:21:45,102
and surveillance videos showed
that he was inside the vehicle...

249
00:21:45,178 --> 00:21:47,510
Leaving him among the 63 dead.

250
00:21:47,581 --> 00:21:50,141
Does anyone not remember this?

251
00:21:51,918 --> 00:21:53,943
You all remember the results
of the investigation?

252
00:21:54,020 --> 00:21:57,820
- They said Scobee acted alone.
- One man, no conspirators.

253
00:21:58,892 --> 00:22:00,689
Right?

254
00:22:01,494 --> 00:22:05,590
He cheated the IRS. They caught
him at it, so he blew 'em up.

255
00:22:08,268 --> 00:22:12,500
This is a guy who people
described as average.

256
00:22:12,572 --> 00:22:14,005
Friendly.

257
00:22:15,342 --> 00:22:18,573
He'd been in the army,
but as a radio man.

258
00:22:18,645 --> 00:22:21,341
He had very little experience
with munitions.

259
00:22:21,414 --> 00:22:25,544
His parents considered him
a moderate conservative.

260
00:22:25,619 --> 00:22:31,353
Two weeks prior to this, he received
a pay raise at his electrician's job.

261
00:22:31,424 --> 00:22:35,360
Does that sound like a man who's
on the edge or a man who needed a push?

262
00:22:35,428 --> 00:22:37,225
Huh?

263
00:22:37,297 --> 00:22:39,663
Come on. I don't know.
I'm just asking.

264
00:22:39,733 --> 00:22:43,669
Come on, Professor.
The Feds did this huge investigation.

265
00:22:43,737 --> 00:22:46,035
That's right,
an investigation, I forgot.

266
00:22:46,106 --> 00:22:48,233
Well...

267
00:22:48,308 --> 00:22:51,243
the investigation
didn't satisfy me.

268
00:22:53,213 --> 00:22:55,841
Miss O'Neill,
when you first heard the news--

269
00:22:55,916 --> 00:22:59,875
terrorist attack in your own country--
how did that make you feel?

270
00:22:59,953 --> 00:23:01,545
- Come on.
- Well--

271
00:23:02,622 --> 00:23:05,648
What did you feel?

272
00:23:05,725 --> 00:23:07,158
Angry.

273
00:23:08,228 --> 00:23:10,287
Scared and stressed.

274
00:23:10,363 --> 00:23:12,923
- Did you feel safe?
- No.

275
00:23:14,000 --> 00:23:18,369
And then the next day,
when they found Scobee dead...

276
00:23:18,438 --> 00:23:20,633
did you feel some relief?

277
00:23:20,707 --> 00:23:22,641
Did safety return?

278
00:23:35,355 --> 00:23:38,051
The people in that building,
they felt safe...

279
00:23:39,693 --> 00:23:44,426
secure, just like you feel now.

280
00:23:46,866 --> 00:23:49,664
And then an instant later--

281
00:23:51,604 --> 00:23:53,538
In an instant...

282
00:23:56,710 --> 00:23:59,645
they were gone forever.

283
00:24:06,686 --> 00:24:10,213
We needed to have
this man to blame.

284
00:24:14,194 --> 00:24:16,424
We don't want others.

285
00:24:16,496 --> 00:24:18,691
We want one name...

286
00:24:18,765 --> 00:24:20,858
and we want it fast...

287
00:24:20,934 --> 00:24:24,700
because it gives us
our security back.

288
00:24:27,674 --> 00:24:30,404
We can say,
"Here was the one man...

289
00:24:30,477 --> 00:24:32,570
unlike the rest of us.

290
00:24:33,880 --> 00:24:37,509
We named him,
and he's no more.

291
00:24:37,584 --> 00:24:40,212
And his reasons,
they're gone too."

292
00:24:40,286 --> 00:24:43,312
But the truth is,
we don't know his reasons.

293
00:24:43,390 --> 00:24:46,154
We don't know why Scobee did it,
why it came to this.

294
00:24:46,226 --> 00:24:49,161
We can pretend we do--
the ten grand in taxes--

295
00:24:49,229 --> 00:24:51,163
but we don't know...

296
00:24:52,232 --> 00:24:54,166
and we'll never know.

297
00:24:57,170 --> 00:25:01,072
And still, we feel sate...

298
00:25:04,778 --> 00:25:07,246
because we know his name.

299
00:25:08,648 --> 00:25:11,742
As God is my witness...

300
00:25:11,818 --> 00:25:14,480
I promise to give...

301
00:25:14,554 --> 00:25:16,488
friendship to those in need.

302
00:25:18,658 --> 00:25:20,649
Help to those in trouble.

303
00:25:22,395 --> 00:25:25,159
I will work with faith and honor...

304
00:25:27,167 --> 00:25:29,397
to uphold the Discoverer code.

305
00:25:32,138 --> 00:25:34,436
To respect myself...

306
00:25:35,308 --> 00:25:37,242
my family...

307
00:25:37,310 --> 00:25:39,244
and my country.

308
00:25:40,346 --> 00:25:43,873
Ladies and gentlemen, please welcome
Junior Discovery Troop 474.

309
00:25:59,466 --> 00:26:01,559
This is Oliver's study...

310
00:26:01,634 --> 00:26:03,864
where he, you know,
gets away from the kids...

311
00:26:03,937 --> 00:26:05,871
and me, I suppose.

312
00:26:07,474 --> 00:26:10,204
These are all projects
you've worked on?

313
00:26:10,276 --> 00:26:12,608
I wish.
No, I collect sketches...

314
00:26:12,679 --> 00:26:15,239
blueprints,
designs of old buildings.

315
00:26:15,315 --> 00:26:17,545
This is a front view of Monticello.

316
00:26:17,617 --> 00:26:20,051
- Down there is the Woolworth Building.
- It's his hobby.

317
00:26:20,120 --> 00:26:23,112
- The St. Louis Arch.
- Yes, correct.

318
00:26:23,890 --> 00:26:26,882
So, then all of these drawings,
these buildings...

319
00:26:26,960 --> 00:26:28,894
they're not just
for your job, then?

320
00:26:30,497 --> 00:26:32,624
Oh. So they're not
all shopping malls.

321
00:26:32,699 --> 00:26:37,033
No, I don't know of any architecturally
significant shopping malls.

322
00:26:37,103 --> 00:26:40,072
Oh, honey, you just
haven't built them yet.

323
00:26:43,276 --> 00:26:45,244
- Who's hungry?
- I'm famished.

324
00:26:45,311 --> 00:26:49,680
Come on. I've got some
really delicious putt pastry.

325
00:26:52,418 --> 00:26:54,511
They've got to work so hard
when they're there.

326
00:26:54,587 --> 00:26:57,112
You've gotta keep 'em
in the seats.

327
00:26:57,190 --> 00:26:58,623
You know?

328
00:26:59,826 --> 00:27:02,727
Politically, there's something
to be said for that.

329
00:27:02,795 --> 00:27:05,093
Yeah, it was a lot of fun.
Here we are leaving the church.

330
00:27:05,165 --> 00:27:07,224
Everyone thought we were
going to Mexico.

331
00:27:07,300 --> 00:27:09,268
- Where were you going?
- We were going there...

332
00:27:09,335 --> 00:27:11,895
but the plane
never left the ground.

333
00:27:11,971 --> 00:27:13,632
Some kind of engine trouble.

334
00:27:13,706 --> 00:27:18,643
Couldn't leave till morning, so we spent
the night at the Wichita Airport Motel.

335
00:27:18,711 --> 00:27:20,872
How romantic!

336
00:27:20,947 --> 00:27:24,508
- Well, for $19, it was wonderful.
- How long you two been married?

337
00:27:25,618 --> 00:27:29,281
- Well, 12 years in August.
- What kind of example is that?

338
00:27:30,356 --> 00:27:35,658
Well, I don't think we learn
responsibility from politicians.

339
00:27:35,728 --> 00:27:37,821
We really learn it from family.

340
00:27:37,897 --> 00:27:40,161
It's the people that we care about.

341
00:27:40,233 --> 00:27:43,862
- It's what they care about.
- He died when I was a teenager.

342
00:27:44,837 --> 00:27:46,634
Oh, I'm sorry.

343
00:27:46,706 --> 00:27:48,139
Farm accident.

344
00:27:50,376 --> 00:27:53,004
-Where would you say you get yours from?
-My what? My values?

345
00:27:58,384 --> 00:28:01,080
- Probably from my wife.
- Values?

346
00:28:02,155 --> 00:28:04,180
What values?

347
00:28:04,257 --> 00:28:07,158
Michael and I were talking about
where you get your values from...

348
00:28:07,227 --> 00:28:09,957
and we were both saying
it's mostly from family.

349
00:28:10,029 --> 00:28:13,726
Well, where else you gonna get 'em?
Celebrities? Politicians?

350
00:28:13,800 --> 00:28:15,734
Not in this century.

351
00:28:18,004 --> 00:28:20,029
I just think it's...

352
00:28:20,106 --> 00:28:24,440
a sorry state of affairs when you can't
find a role model to cast your vote for.

353
00:28:24,510 --> 00:28:26,944
It's not even role models,
necessarily.

354
00:28:27,013 --> 00:28:31,882
It's just people who acknowledge
the consequences of their actions.

355
00:28:31,951 --> 00:28:36,820
Or pay for those actions. I think we
should put some politicians in jail.

356
00:28:38,358 --> 00:28:41,418
You can't ask government
to be infallible.

357
00:28:41,494 --> 00:28:44,122
You just can't.
But you can ask it to be accountable.

358
00:28:46,899 --> 00:28:49,231
I can ask it to be honest.

359
00:28:49,302 --> 00:28:51,964
You know, when Leah died...

360
00:28:52,038 --> 00:28:55,235
all I wanted was someone...

361
00:28:55,308 --> 00:28:59,108
to tell me,
"We made a mistake."

362
00:28:59,178 --> 00:29:02,670
You know?
"We made a mistake.

363
00:29:02,749 --> 00:29:04,944
Your wife suffered for it...

364
00:29:06,019 --> 00:29:08,453
and we'd take it back
a hundred times if we could."

365
00:29:09,289 --> 00:29:11,484
But, uh...

366
00:29:11,557 --> 00:29:13,957
they don't say that.

367
00:29:14,027 --> 00:29:15,460
She would've.

368
00:29:21,567 --> 00:29:24,331
Some of them knew her.

369
00:29:29,108 --> 00:29:32,635
They work so hard at being able
to look you in the eye.

370
00:29:51,931 --> 00:29:53,296
Excuse me.

371
00:30:07,146 --> 00:30:09,239
Leave him alone.
He's tine.

372
00:30:13,453 --> 00:30:14,886
Sorry.

373
00:30:23,029 --> 00:30:25,862
- I see how much you miss her.
- There are just these times...

374
00:30:25,932 --> 00:30:29,834
when you realize how much
your own life is out of your hands.

375
00:30:33,272 --> 00:30:35,365
What are you gonna do?

376
00:30:39,312 --> 00:30:41,405
I guess you can have faith.

377
00:30:44,217 --> 00:30:47,584
Try to make a difference
while you can with Grant...

378
00:30:49,389 --> 00:30:51,323
to your classes.

379
00:30:55,928 --> 00:30:57,862
What about you?

380
00:31:00,767 --> 00:31:02,701
Got my family...

381
00:31:04,737 --> 00:31:06,932
and the buildings I leave behind.

382
00:31:11,644 --> 00:31:13,578
That's it.

383
00:31:13,646 --> 00:31:15,978
Get your shoulder up
a little bit, okay?

384
00:31:16,048 --> 00:31:18,846
Step into it. Watch that ball
until it hits the bat.

385
00:31:18,918 --> 00:31:20,852
That's it!

386
00:31:22,955 --> 00:31:25,048
You want some Crackerjack?

387
00:31:29,295 --> 00:31:33,789
You sure? Popcorn and caramel.
It builds your muscles.

388
00:31:33,866 --> 00:31:35,231
All right.

389
00:31:37,103 --> 00:31:39,037
Hey, atta way, Faraday.

390
00:31:40,339 --> 00:31:44,537
- He's gettin' some confidence.
- He's a strong kid.

391
00:31:46,479 --> 00:31:49,846
- He's been dealt some hard breaks.
- Atta way to swing.

392
00:31:51,517 --> 00:31:55,112
- You give him strength.
- I'm tryin'.

393
00:31:55,188 --> 00:31:57,383
You do.

394
00:31:57,457 --> 00:32:00,255
Gettin' on with your life.
That's important for him to see.

395
00:32:02,895 --> 00:32:05,159
He just wishes someone had to pay.

396
00:32:06,265 --> 00:32:07,391
What?

397
00:32:08,768 --> 00:32:12,670
For his mother.
He wishes someone had to pay.

398
00:32:12,738 --> 00:32:14,831
He's talked to you about her?

399
00:32:16,242 --> 00:32:18,642
Our people send her in with
the wrong information then say...

400
00:32:18,711 --> 00:32:20,645
"Hey, not my fault."

401
00:32:22,982 --> 00:32:25,143
I can't live with that...

402
00:32:25,218 --> 00:32:28,415
for you,
let alone a nine-year-old boy.

403
00:32:29,856 --> 00:32:32,484
Grant talked to you
about his mother?

404
00:32:34,594 --> 00:32:36,186
Well, yeah.

405
00:32:36,262 --> 00:32:39,663
I hope that's all right.
We talk about a lot of things.

406
00:32:41,300 --> 00:32:43,325
He's a smart kid.

407
00:32:46,405 --> 00:32:48,930
Way to go, Grant.

408
00:32:50,910 --> 00:32:53,504
We're never more wise
than when we're children.

409
00:32:53,579 --> 00:32:55,513
They say it, and it's true.

410
00:32:57,283 --> 00:32:59,751
We'll never see things
that clear again.

411
00:33:05,525 --> 00:33:07,618
Let me have a hit.

412
